  "prompt": "Does a voltmeter show RMS voltage?",
  "response": "Whether a voltmeter shows RMS (Root Mean Square) voltage depends on the type of voltmeter being used.\n\n1. **Analog Voltmeters**:\n   - Some analog voltmeters are designed to measure the average value of the voltage rather than the RMS value. For sinusoidal waveforms, this can be adjusted to display RMS voltage by applying a calibration factor (since for a sine wave, RMS value = Average value / 0.707).\n\n2. **Digital Voltmeters**:\n   - Most modern digital voltmeters are designed to measure and display the true RMS voltage. They use integrated circuits that calculate the RMS value of the voltage, regardless of the waveform shape (whether sinusoidal, square, triangular, etc.).\n\n3. **Specialized True RMS Voltmeters**:\n   - These voltmeters are specifically designed to measure the true RMS value of any waveform, including non-sinusoidal waveforms. They are more accurate for complex or distorted waveforms.\n\nIn summary, if the voltmeter is labeled as a \"true RMS\" voltmeter, it will display the RMS voltage. Otherwise, it may display the average voltage, which for sinusoidal waveforms, can be converted to RMS using the appropriate factor. Always refer to the specifications of the voltmeter to determine what it measures.",
